00:13:15.450 --> 00:13:18.260
So he moves himself to
Baghdad in 2003 to wait

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:20.110
for the Americans to arrive.

00:13:20.110 --> 00:13:22.640
So when he gets there, he
starts to build alliances.

00:13:22.640 --> 00:13:25.590
Here's this crazy guy that wants
to start a terrorist movement.

00:13:25.590 --> 00:13:27.290
Suddenly, he's got
all kinds of allies

00:13:27.290 --> 00:13:30.340
because the Iraqi army has been
disbanded, all those colonels

00:13:30.340 --> 00:13:32.930
and generals and majors
don't have jobs anymore

00:13:32.930 --> 00:13:34.440
so they're looking to fight back.

00:13:34.440 --> 00:13:35.740
You've got the Ba'athist Party.

00:13:35.740 --> 00:13:38.810
Everybody who is a professional
in Iraq was a Ba'athist.

00:13:38.810 --> 00:13:41.000
Suddenly all those people
are looking for leadership

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:43.750
and Zarqawi moves into that
fact and he becomes the nucleus

00:13:43.750 --> 00:13:47.910
for this new insurgency that we
began to see unfolding in 2003.

00:13:47.910 --> 00:13:50.100
He's got a good head for
strategy and he starts going

00:13:50.100 --> 00:13:52.530
out after some very
important targets.

00:13:52.530 --> 00:13:54.300
He goes after the UN headquarters.

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.270
He kills the leader of
the UN mission in Iraq.

00:13:56.270 --> 00:13:59.350
He goes after NGOs, the Red
Cross, all kinds of groups

00:13:59.350 --> 00:14:00.650
that would help the United States,

00:14:00.650 --> 00:14:03.820
who would give us the cover
legitimacy, drives them home.

00:14:03.820 --> 00:14:05.640
And then, more importantly,

00:14:05.640 --> 00:14:08.590
he goes after the Sunni-Shia
divide in this country.

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:13.050 position:56%
Sunnis and Shiites have been living
together reasonably well for decades

00:14:13.050 --> 00:14:15.830
but Zarqawi decides very
deliberately to start a Civil War.

00:14:15.830 --> 00:14:17.760
So he blows up their
most important mosque.

00:14:17.760 --> 00:14:21.000
He kills their leaders and suddenly
you have appraisal killings you've

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:23.320
got essentially shooting back
and forth between two groups

00:14:23.320 --> 00:14:25.550
that had gotten along
pretty good together.

00:14:25.550 --> 00:14:28.750
So strategically, you think about
what he did, it was pretty smart.

00:14:28.750 --> 00:14:32.580
He isolated us in Iraq then he
sets off a civil war around us

00:14:32.580 --> 00:14:35.920
and we're-- By 2004, 2005, we're
in pretty bad shape in terms

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:39.200
of our occupation and
our plans for Iraq.

00:14:39.200 --> 00:14:43.320
So, the next thing that happened,
this is kind of background noise

00:14:43.320 --> 00:14:45.760
for Zarqawi because he's
got bigger ambitions.

00:14:45.760 --> 00:14:48.230
He wants to become an
international star.

00:14:48.230 --> 00:14:49.890
He feels he has a destiny.

00:14:49.890 --> 00:14:53.990
And so he develops this notion that
no matter what kind of bombing,

00:14:53.990 --> 00:14:55.770
what kind of shooting
you might be able to do,

00:14:55.770 --> 00:14:57.360
there's nothing that's
more gripping,

00:14:57.360 --> 00:15:01.600
that's more so viscerally horrible
than watching a single execution.

00:15:01.600 --> 00:15:04.070
So he grabs a random
American off the street,

00:15:04.070 --> 00:15:06.490
this is a kid named Nick
Berg from Philadelphia.

00:15:06.490 --> 00:15:08.240
He takes him into his cell.

00:15:08.240 --> 00:15:10.440
He sits him down with
an orange jumpsuit,

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:13.170
the image we were also familiar
with and he personally--

00:15:13.170 --> 00:15:15.060
that's Zarqawi reading
the script there.

00:15:15.060 --> 00:15:17.940
He personally beheads this
young man with his own hand.

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:19.370
This becomes his calling card.

00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:21.360
Many beheadings will follow.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.560
The violence that Zarqawi
unleashes just tears up the country

00:15:24.560 --> 00:15:27.330 position:56%
and it's too much even for Al-Qaeda.

00:15:27.330 --> 00:15:29.050
And so that's not the
only difference.

00:15:29.050 --> 00:15:32.950
Zarqawi begins to launch a new
media campaign with himself

00:15:32.950 --> 00:15:36.250
at the center using social media
platforms just becoming available.

00:15:36.250 --> 00:15:40.900 position:56%
So he got the gray-bearded Osama bin
Laden, you know, reading his sermons

00:15:40.900 --> 00:15:43.230
from behind a, you know,
a podium, very boring,

00:15:43.230 --> 00:15:45.990
and then you've got this
jihadist action figure,

00:15:45.990 --> 00:15:48.130
like a black ninja
firing his machine gun,

00:15:48.130 --> 00:15:50.320
killing Americans with
his own hands.

00:15:50.320 --> 00:15:52.870
Young jihadists around
the world eat this up.

00:15:52.870 --> 00:15:56.250
And then he's brash enough to make
up his own rules because remember,

00:15:56.250 --> 00:15:58.260
he's not even a high
school graduate.

00:15:58.260 --> 00:16:01.010
He's not very smart but he
does understand theology

00:16:01.010 --> 00:16:04.880
and that's liberating to him
because he doesn't bother to worry

00:16:04.880 --> 00:16:08.020
about whether he is committing
acts that aren't very Islamic,

00:16:08.020 --> 00:16:11.810 position:56%
like targeting innocent Muslim women
and children and suicide attacks.

00:16:11.810 --> 00:16:15.210
Then he begins to think about a
really big idea which is the idea

00:16:15.210 --> 00:16:17.230
of restoring the ancient caliphate,

00:16:17.230 --> 00:16:20.830
the Islamic theocratic
empire of the centuries past.

00:16:20.830 --> 00:16:24.560
He regards himself as divinely
inspired to usher in this new age

00:16:24.560 --> 00:16:28.200
of ultra pure Islam, driving
out western governments along

00:16:28.200 --> 00:16:31.270
with brutally destroying everyone
else that stands in his way,

00:16:31.270 --> 00:16:35.290
from corrupt governments to
apostate sex like the Shiites.

00:16:35.290 --> 00:16:39.170
And this struggle would end in a
mighty battle, in an Armageddon,

00:16:39.170 --> 00:16:41.630
in which armies of Islam would
finally defeat the armies

00:16:41.630 --> 00:16:44.080
of Christianity as some
prophets have foretold.

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:46.380
This was going to be
Zarqawi's role of history.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:49.370
"I am the spark," he used to say.

00:16:49.370 --> 00:16:51.840
Well, he didn't get to see
any of it because Zarqawi was

00:16:51.840 --> 00:16:54.170
by now republic enemy number one.

00:16:54.170 --> 00:16:57.660
We poured vast resources
into this effort to stop him.

00:16:57.660 --> 00:17:00.990
It took us nearly three years to
track him down but eventually,

00:17:00.990 --> 00:17:05.400 position:56%
our Intel, our ground forces special
operation teams found a formula

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:07.340
for defeating Zarqawi
and his network.

00:17:07.340 --> 00:17:08.840
We find his safe house.

00:17:08.840 --> 00:17:11.320
In 2006, we drop a
couple of bombs on it

00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:13.230
and that's the end
of Zarqawi himself.

00:17:13.230 --> 00:17:15.640
We start dismantling the
leadership, killing number twos

00:17:15.640 --> 00:17:17.870
and number threes,
raiding safe houses.

00:17:17.870 --> 00:17:19.930
And just as we're figuring
all this out,

00:17:19.930 --> 00:17:21.840
other things happened
that are helping us.

00:17:21.840 --> 00:17:24.670
The Iraqi Sunni tribes revolt
against Zarqawi's followers

00:17:24.670 --> 00:17:26.570
and we have this thing
called the "Anbar Awakening".

00:17:26.570 --> 00:17:29.320
The US troops search happens.

00:17:29.320 --> 00:17:32.730
And by 2009, all that's left
was just a few hundred followers

00:17:32.730 --> 00:17:35.960
who have been driven deep
underground in hiding.

00:17:35.960 --> 00:17:39.020
Al-Qaeda in Iraq was
essentially beaten,

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:41.190
but not everybody thought so.

00:17:41.190 --> 00:17:43.130
Here's our second ISIS personality.

00:17:43.130 --> 00:17:45.640
We now know him as
Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi.

00:17:45.640 --> 00:17:47.600
He's the leader of ISIS today.

00:17:47.600 --> 00:17:50.440
In Zarqawi's time, nobody would
have pictured him as a leader.

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:53.610
He was in many ways
Zarqawi's opposite, a scholar,

00:17:53.610 --> 00:17:55.460
kind of shy, kind of boring.

00:17:55.460 --> 00:17:58.120
His family and friends remember
him as this kid that never spoke

00:17:58.120 --> 00:18:01.610
to anyone, carried books around his
bicycle, wasn't very impressive.

00:18:01.610 --> 00:18:04.300
He has a doctor degree
in Islamic law,

00:18:04.300 --> 00:18:06.530
his own track to becoming
a college professor

00:18:06.530 --> 00:18:09.420
when the US invasion
takes place in 2003.

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:12.810
Baghdadi joins Zarqawi's
gang because he feels obliged

00:18:12.810 --> 00:18:14.870
as a good Muslim to
fight the infidel.

00:18:14.870 --> 00:18:16.750 position:56%
So he becomes part of this movement.

00:18:16.750 --> 00:18:18.240 position:56%
He ends up going to jail for awhile.

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:20.310
Once again, he has the
prison experience exposed

00:18:20.310 --> 00:18:22.460
to these tough guys around him.

00:18:22.460 --> 00:18:26.180 position:56%
And-- but-- then he gets-- he starts
to rise up to the ranks mostly

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:30.310
because other leaders around
him by 2010 are getting killed.

00:18:30.310 --> 00:18:33.570
And so in 2010, the leaders
of this battered organization,

00:18:33.570 --> 00:18:36.190
mostly former Iraqi army
officers by this time,

00:18:36.190 --> 00:18:37.990
decide they need a
different kind of figurehead.

00:18:37.990 --> 00:18:40.810
And so they pick this guy Baghdadi.

00:18:40.810 --> 00:18:42.110
He's an Islamic scholar.

00:18:42.110 --> 00:18:45.070
He happens to be from a tribe
that can trace his lineage back

00:18:45.070 --> 00:18:48.140
to Muhammad, so he has serious
religious credentials to serve

00:18:48.140 --> 00:18:50.930
as the head of the group that's
no longer calling itself Al-Qaeda

00:18:50.930 --> 00:18:52.230
in Iraq.

00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:55.180
It started to call itself a
state, the Islamic state of Iraq.

00:18:55.180 --> 00:18:57.700
The state part is kind of a
joke because even to these guys,

00:18:57.700 --> 00:18:59.330
they know there's no real state.

00:18:59.330 --> 00:19:02.210
One of the leaders [inaudible]
reacts famously to this new name

00:19:02.210 --> 00:19:04.720
with derision, "Where is the
state you're talking about?

00:19:04.720 --> 00:19:06.300
We're leaving in a desert."

00:19:06.300 --> 00:19:12.940
But history intervenes
again in ISIS's favor.

00:19:12.940 --> 00:19:16.400
Just as Baghdadi is coming to
power, US troops are leaving Iraq

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:18.770
under agreement structure
in the Bush administration.

00:19:18.770 --> 00:19:21.710
And as soon as they're gone, the
Shiite government feels emboldened

00:19:21.710 --> 00:19:24.450
to start settling old
scores with Sunni tribes,

00:19:24.450 --> 00:19:27.450
arresting their leaders,
kicking out Sunni army officers.

00:19:27.450 --> 00:19:30.310
And so much of the Sunni
population begins to rebel

00:19:30.310 --> 00:19:34.300
against the Baghdadi government,
finding more interest in common

00:19:34.300 --> 00:19:38.670
with Zarqawi's people, with ISIS,
then with their own government.

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:40.930
And then a year later,
the Civil War breaks

00:19:40.930 --> 00:19:43.120
out in Syria as we all well know.

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:47.000
And this is a pivotal moment
because it's an opportunity

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:49.040
for these guys to start
something new.

00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:51.170
They start their own
militia group inside Syria.

00:19:51.170 --> 00:19:54.500
They have a perfect incubator
now with a lawless state washed

00:19:54.500 --> 00:19:57.700
in violence and weapons,
and they have a new cause,

00:19:57.700 --> 00:20:00.980
fighting an oppressive dictator,
Assad, a man who's stirring

00:20:00.980 --> 00:20:03.020
up passions all over
the Islamic world

00:20:03.020 --> 00:20:05.620
by slaughtering Sunni
Arab civilians.

00:20:05.620 --> 00:20:09.040
They renamed themselves yet again
and now they're Islamic state

00:20:09.040 --> 00:20:13.540
of Iraq and al-Sham or ISIS and
they're extraordinarily accessible

00:20:13.540 --> 00:20:16.040
and almost immediately because
they're battle-hardened,

00:20:16.040 --> 00:20:18.540
they're the best fighters in
the rebel side and they start

00:20:18.540 --> 00:20:22.010
to attract foreign
recruits by the thousands.

00:20:22.010 --> 00:20:25.740
By 2014, they're ready to break out
and they do so in dramatic fashion,

00:20:25.740 --> 00:20:28.670
capturing the eastern half
of Syria then invading Iraq

00:20:28.670 --> 00:20:31.340
to declare the establishment
of this Islamic caliphate.

00:20:31.340 --> 00:20:35.410
By the summer of 2014, they're
a powerhouse, 30,000 strong,

00:20:35.410 --> 00:20:38.870
able to conquer major Iraqi
cities, overrun entire divisions

00:20:38.870 --> 00:20:40.640
of US trained Iraqi troops.

00:20:40.640 --> 00:20:43.450
This is the ISIS we're
so familiar with today.

00:20:43.450 --> 00:20:46.240
And they're also very rich
because after capturing Mosul,

00:20:46.240 --> 00:20:48.090
they said they have
become the wealthiest

00:20:48.090 --> 00:20:50.050
and best armed terrorist
group of all time.

00:20:50.050 --> 00:20:51.350
They own oil wells.

00:20:51.350 --> 00:20:53.850
They own banks, universities,
hundreds of millions

00:20:53.850 --> 00:20:55.340
of dollars in hard currency.

00:20:55.340 --> 00:20:58.880
These are resources the Al-Qaeda
would have only dreamed of having.

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:00.670
And-- but really, beyond
their wealth,

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:02.930
it's Zarqawi's old organization.

00:21:02.930 --> 00:21:05.270
Zarqawi embraced violence
for its own sake.

00:21:05.270 --> 00:21:09.120
These guys do the same
thing on a grander scale.

00:21:09.120 --> 00:21:10.630
They also have this boldness

00:21:10.630 --> 00:21:13.500
to reinterpret Islam in
any way they want to.

00:21:13.500 --> 00:21:16.550
As-- Baghdadi is a religious
scholar so he goes out of his way

00:21:16.550 --> 00:21:20.580
to create theological arguments to
justify whatever atrocity they do.

00:21:20.580 --> 00:21:23.660
There's always a verse in the Quran
or a tradition in the hadith text

00:21:23.660 --> 00:21:26.120
that can be made to justify--

00:21:26.120 --> 00:21:30.350
make themselves appear to be pious
Muslims instead of just barbarians.

00:21:30.350 --> 00:21:33.290
And just as Zarqawi understood
that the horror can be amplified

00:21:33.290 --> 00:21:36.310
on a massive scale using the
internet, ISIS did the same

00:21:36.310 --> 00:21:37.780
and just got better at it.

00:21:37.780 --> 00:21:40.390 position:56%
They're extremely skilled in
harnessing the power of social media

00:21:40.390 --> 00:21:43.560
for recruitment, for screening,
for indoctrination, for training,

00:21:43.560 --> 00:21:44.860
all of which can be done

00:21:44.860 --> 00:21:48.920
at a distance before the recruit
even sets foot in Syrian soil.

00:21:48.920 --> 00:21:52.260
But now instead of the shaky
handheld videos that Zarqawi used

00:21:52.260 --> 00:21:55.480
to use, they have teams of
professional, videographers,

00:21:55.480 --> 00:21:59.670 position:56%
editors, graphic artists, working on
products aimed at young men who grew

00:21:59.670 --> 00:22:03.380
up on army like video
games, like Call of Duty.

00:22:03.380 --> 00:22:07.820
This formula works and the idea of
ISIS becomes a powerful attraction.

00:22:07.820 --> 00:22:10.670
Thirty-five thousand foreigners
travel to the caliphate

00:22:10.670 --> 00:22:13.830
to join this army, far surpassing
the number of foreign fighters

00:22:13.830 --> 00:22:18.170 position:56%
who joined Al-Qaeda and
Afghanistan or Zarqawi's Iraqi army.

00:22:18.170 --> 00:22:19.880
The movement metastasizes.

00:22:19.880 --> 00:22:23.230
In a year, there are nine mini
states of ISIS around the world

00:22:23.230 --> 00:22:27.690
in cells and dozens of places
including about 5000 ISIS recruits

00:22:27.690 --> 00:22:30.130
from Europe alone,
which brings us quickly

00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:32.680
to our next personality
that defines ISIS today.

00:22:32.680 --> 00:22:34.440
You may not recognize
his name or image

00:22:34.440 --> 00:22:35.970
but you'll remember what he did.

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:40.320
This is Abdelhamid Abaaoud, who's
a 28-year-old Belgian national

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:41.680
who led the terrorist attack

00:22:41.680 --> 00:22:45.050
in Paris last November
that killed 130 people.

00:22:45.050 --> 00:22:48.040
His background is actually very
close to this typical prototype

00:22:48.040 --> 00:22:51.380
of Northern Europeans who joined
ISIS, the son of Muslim immigrants

00:22:51.380 --> 00:22:53.650
from North Africa, so
a second generation,

00:22:53.650 --> 00:22:55.730
a troubled youth well-known
to police.

00:22:55.730 --> 00:23:00.010
He lived in Islam made up of
middle class Muslim immigrants.

00:23:00.010 --> 00:23:02.990
He's a kid that truly didn't
fit in in his society of--

00:23:02.990 --> 00:23:05.220
he's not really a religious Muslim.

00:23:05.220 --> 00:23:09.120
He's not really a modern citizen
of his family's adopted country.

00:23:09.120 --> 00:23:12.200
He ends up being radicalized in
prison and when he joins ISIS,

00:23:12.200 --> 00:23:15.800
he suddenly has two things he never
had before, a sense of belonging

00:23:15.800 --> 00:23:20.850
and a cause, something that allows
this misbehaved misfit to feel

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:22.850
as though his life
counts for something.

00:23:22.850 --> 00:23:25.680
He travels to Syria and
initially he's a bit distressed

00:23:25.680 --> 00:23:26.980
by the bloodshed.

00:23:26.980 --> 00:23:29.280
A few months later, he's
fully with the program.

00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:33.570
He's posting videos of himself
dragging corpses behind cars.

00:23:33.570 --> 00:23:35.890
He becomes a key coordinator
for the ISIS attack

00:23:35.890 --> 00:23:37.690
in Paris as we all well remember.

00:23:37.690 --> 00:23:41.360
It was the biggest and-- his
biggest and final assignment.

00:23:41.360 --> 00:23:44.300
The two things we have to
remember about him when we think

00:23:44.300 --> 00:23:47.880
about the story is, one, he's
emblematic of a population

00:23:47.880 --> 00:23:50.880
that is particularly
vulnerable to ISIS's message,

00:23:50.880 --> 00:23:53.910
nearly always second
generation, children of immigrants

00:23:53.910 --> 00:23:57.330
who feel conflicted about their
identities and not well-integrated

00:23:57.330 --> 00:23:59.630
in their societies,
struggling personally,

00:23:59.630 --> 00:24:02.320
don't seem to have a sense
of purpose or future.

00:24:02.320 --> 00:24:04.440
They're looking for
meaning and for adventure

00:24:04.440 --> 00:24:06.820
and ISIS offers all
those things for them.

00:24:06.820 --> 00:24:09.790
The second key thing, a
primary reason ISIS carries

00:24:09.790 --> 00:24:13.080
out attacks abroad is it
wants young men like Abaaoud

00:24:13.080 --> 00:24:15.080
to feel even more alienated.

00:24:15.080 --> 00:24:18.130
The more countries feel threatened
by ISIS, the greater the tendency

00:24:18.130 --> 00:24:21.790
to crack down on young Muslims,
to profile them, to harass them,

00:24:21.790 --> 00:24:23.670
to make them feel even
more alienated.

00:24:23.670 --> 00:24:24.970
How do we know this?

00:24:24.970 --> 00:24:27.190
ISIS talks about it
in its own literature.

00:24:27.190 --> 00:24:29.220
Just before the Paris
attack last November,

00:24:29.220 --> 00:24:32.430
ISIS's English language magazine
puts out an article that talks

00:24:32.430 --> 00:24:34.460
about the gray zone in Europe.

00:24:34.460 --> 00:24:38.000
This is the zone where
millions of Muslims inhabit.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:40.680
They feel conflicted about
their identity and ISIS wants

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:42.450
to force them to choose sides.

00:24:42.450 --> 00:24:44.360
The article says this, "Muslims

00:24:44.360 --> 00:24:48.180
in the west will quickly find
themselves between two choices,

00:24:48.180 --> 00:24:52.170 position:56%
either they apostatize and adopt the
infidel religion or they immigrate

00:24:52.170 --> 00:24:54.860
to the Islamic state
and escape prosecution."

00:24:54.860 --> 00:24:58.210
This is a binary choice for
ISIS and it welcomes our help

00:24:58.210 --> 00:25:00.230
in driving Muslims to their corner.

00:25:00.230 --> 00:25:02.600
For us in the west, the
solutions that seem easiest

00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:05.070
and most politically
palpable are often the ones

00:25:05.070 --> 00:25:07.460
that get us in a deeper hole.

00:25:07.460 --> 00:25:09.940
Real quickly, the fourth
ISIS personality to talk

00:25:09.940 --> 00:25:12.390
about was never really
a member of ISIS.

00:25:12.390 --> 00:25:15.540
Yet we all associate Omar
Mateen with the Islamic state.

00:25:15.540 --> 00:25:17.770
This is the young man who
walked into the Pulse Nightclub

00:25:17.770 --> 00:25:20.250
in Orlando last June
and killed 49 people

00:25:20.250 --> 00:25:22.360
in the worst mass shooting
in US history.

00:25:22.360 --> 00:25:24.600
Mateen told police
he did it for ISIS.

00:25:24.600 --> 00:25:27.440
Today, there's no evidence that
he had any contact with ISIS

00:25:27.440 --> 00:25:28.950
in a serious way and in fact,

00:25:28.950 --> 00:25:33.260 position:56%
his statement suggest a very limited
grasp of ISIS's belief and ideology

00:25:33.260 --> 00:25:35.770
and yet, ISIS gets credit
for the attack anyway

00:25:35.770 --> 00:25:39.190
and it becomes a talking point
in our political discourse.

00:25:39.190 --> 00:25:41.930
Here's what's interesting again
to me about Mateen's story.

00:25:41.930 --> 00:25:44.970
It's another young man
who fits the profile

00:25:44.970 --> 00:25:47.720
of a typical Northern
European ISIS recruit,

00:25:47.720 --> 00:25:50.370
the son of Muslim immigrant,
second generation again.

00:25:50.370 --> 00:25:52.480
A young man in his 20s
with a troubled background,

00:25:52.480 --> 00:25:56.430
unable to find personal success
in his life and feeling excluded

00:25:56.430 --> 00:25:58.640
and persecuted by the
dominant culture.

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:00.980
So he embraces an extremist
ideology as a way

00:26:00.980 --> 00:26:03.020
to feel empowered and important.

00:26:03.020 --> 00:26:06.220
Even more striking to me is that
Mateen fits another profile,

00:26:06.220 --> 00:26:09.240
that of the typical perpetrator of
an American mass shooting event.

00:26:09.240 --> 00:26:10.870
There's an interesting
piece actually

00:26:10.870 --> 00:26:12.760
in today's Washington Post
that makes this point.

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:16.580
It notes that "Islamic extremist
like Mateen share many of these--

00:26:16.580 --> 00:26:20.170
the same traits as regular mass
killers, if we can call them that.

00:26:20.170 --> 00:26:22.110
Almost all our young
men who struggle to fit

00:26:22.110 --> 00:26:25.690 position:56%
in their communities, they feel
alienated and persecuted in some way

00:26:25.690 --> 00:26:29.440
and they also have a boastfulness
and a craving for attention."

00:26:29.440 --> 00:26:31.680
It's the same profile for
example as Dylann Roof,

00:26:31.680 --> 00:26:34.500
the young man from South
Carolina who shot up a church

00:26:34.500 --> 00:26:37.400
in South Carolina in Charleston
and killed nine people.

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:39.910
One expert in the article
makes his observation.

00:26:39.910 --> 00:26:42.950
Omar Mateen has more in
common with Dylann Roof

00:26:42.950 --> 00:26:44.750
than he does with Osama bin Laden.

00:26:44.750 --> 00:26:47.890
ISIS just offers certain young
men a different kind of excuse

00:26:47.890 --> 00:26:50.360
for carrying out their
revenge fantasies.

00:26:50.360 --> 00:26:52.540
This is pretty dark stuff and
it's pretty depressing so I do

00:26:52.540 --> 00:26:55.590
like to always include the fact
there are reasons to be hopeful

00:26:55.590 --> 00:26:57.010
about our fight right now.

00:26:57.010 --> 00:26:59.020
If you follow the news, you
know the caliphate is really

00:26:59.020 --> 00:27:00.860
from a series of attacks.

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:04.970
They're losing ground about half
of what was once ISIS a territory

00:27:04.970 --> 00:27:07.230
in Iraq is now liberated.

00:27:07.230 --> 00:27:11.080 position:56%
Liberating Iraq means fewer
resources for ISIS, fewer oil cells,

00:27:11.080 --> 00:27:13.790
fewer towns and villages
they can exploit for cash.

00:27:13.790 --> 00:27:16.770
So you see here in this map that
the size of caliphate is shrinking.

00:27:16.770 --> 00:27:21.370
The area in green was once
controlled by ISIS, now it's not.

00:27:21.370 --> 00:27:23.760
They're faltering in
the public relations war

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:25.280
because people see the brutality.

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:26.580
They see the hypocrisy.

00:27:26.580 --> 00:27:28.910
And even young Arab
Muslims, their core audience,

00:27:28.910 --> 00:27:30.340
are starting to turn away.

00:27:30.340 --> 00:27:33.940
This is a look at British
Muslims who turns out.

00:27:33.940 --> 00:27:37.230
So you see just in a year's time,
support or opposition rather

00:27:37.230 --> 00:27:41.020
to ISIS drop from or
[inaudible] from about 65% to 85%.

00:27:41.020 --> 00:27:44.310
It's somewhat disturbing as the
fact that this kind of small group

00:27:44.310 --> 00:27:50.580
of people who embrace the ideology
of ISIS has remained pretty static.

00:27:50.580 --> 00:27:54.400
Other good news, we have
more and more seeing Muslim,

00:27:54.400 --> 00:27:58.000
other Muslim countries, Muslim
Arabs taking on a greater share

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:00.660
of the fight for participation
of the Arab campaign to boots

00:28:00.660 --> 00:28:03.240
on the ground and this
makes them going slower

00:28:03.240 --> 00:28:05.300
but it's usually important
because Arab boots

00:28:05.300 --> 00:28:09.130
in the ground are vastly preferable
to an occupation and invasion

00:28:09.130 --> 00:28:11.530
by outside forces for all
kinds of obvious reasons.

00:28:11.530 --> 00:28:13.000
And it's also encouraging.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:14.770
We're seeing more Muslims
take a public stand

00:28:14.770 --> 00:28:16.910
against this extremist ideology.

00:28:16.910 --> 00:28:19.960
One of the world's great religions
is being attacked from within

00:28:19.960 --> 00:28:22.800
and only other Muslims have
the standing to be able

00:28:22.800 --> 00:28:25.790
to defeat the virulence that has
affected so many young people.

00:28:25.790 --> 00:28:29.470 position:56%
We see the King of Jordan, Abdullah,
organizing an effort by hundreds

00:28:29.470 --> 00:28:33.510
of Muslim clerics from all sects to
denounce extremist interpretation.

00:28:33.510 --> 00:28:37.300
Egypt's President Sisi here goes
to the top of theological seminary

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:41.140
in Cairo to call for an Islamic
reformation, saying to his leaders,

00:28:41.140 --> 00:28:43.990 position:56%
"We have to take back our religion."

00:28:43.990 --> 00:28:47.710
It's a hopeful start but we need
to see a lot more than this.

00:28:47.710 --> 00:28:51.100
And finally, despite the good
news on it from the front lines,

00:28:51.100 --> 00:28:54.280
I can't be optimistic about
defeating this ideology

00:28:54.280 --> 00:28:56.670
in the near term and here is why.

00:28:56.670 --> 00:28:59.470
I introduce my fifth
and final personality.

00:28:59.470 --> 00:29:01.610
I won't use his real name but we'll
call him Ahmad [assumed spelling].

00:29:01.610 --> 00:29:02.910
He's seven years old.

00:29:02.910 --> 00:29:05.250
We met him in a refugee
camp in Germany.

00:29:05.250 --> 00:29:07.970
He was one of thousands of young
children who had lived under ISIS

00:29:07.970 --> 00:29:09.870
in towns and villages
of the caliphate.

00:29:09.870 --> 00:29:12.720
He's a bright, beautiful
young boy who happened to live

00:29:12.720 --> 00:29:15.690
in the Syrian city of
Raqqah when ISIS took over.

00:29:15.690 --> 00:29:18.930 position:56%
Within months, he was in the ISIS
trading camp, getting indoctrinated,

00:29:18.930 --> 00:29:20.390
learning how to use a gun.

00:29:20.390 --> 00:29:22.620
He was taught that his
parents were not good Muslims

00:29:22.620 --> 00:29:24.200
and he should report
any bad behavior

00:29:24.200 --> 00:29:25.790
at home that wasn't Islamic.

00:29:25.790 --> 00:29:27.880
He was taught that the
greatest possible calling

00:29:27.880 --> 00:29:31.050
for young men his age was
to be a suicide bomber.

00:29:31.050 --> 00:29:33.580
Ahmad talked to us about
witnessing executions.

00:29:33.580 --> 00:29:37.010
He talked to us about going to a
local park and finding the bodies

00:29:37.010 --> 00:29:40.190
of men with their severed
heads stacked up next to them.

00:29:40.190 --> 00:29:43.200 position:56%
Every now and then during this
interview, he would shutdown and ask

00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:46.320
for some time-out and at one point,
he asks us for a piece of paper

00:29:46.320 --> 00:29:49.380
so he could draw a
picture of Syria, his home.

00:29:49.380 --> 00:29:50.680
This is what he drew.

00:29:50.680 --> 00:29:56.110 position:56%
He was telling us a story about
something he'd personally witnessed.

00:29:56.110 --> 00:30:00.040
A man with one eye on the
right side was a prisoner

00:30:00.040 --> 00:30:01.950
who was brought into
the town square.

00:30:01.950 --> 00:30:05.030
The man on the left has a
knife and he beheads him.

00:30:05.030 --> 00:30:10.750 position:56%
And then below, you see the one-eyed
man's head lying on the floor.

00:30:10.750 --> 00:30:12.890
We worry in this country
about ISIS recruits,

00:30:12.890 --> 00:30:15.840
about people being radicalized on
the internet or traveling to Iraq

00:30:15.840 --> 00:30:19.020
or Syria to fight but we're
facing entirely different problem

00:30:19.020 --> 00:30:22.040
with the generation of young people
who grew up under this terror.

00:30:22.040 --> 00:30:25.000
I bring this up because when
the caliphate does collapse--

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:27.270
and I think we're beginning
to see the end of it--

00:30:27.270 --> 00:30:29.290
westerners cannot afford
to look away.

00:30:29.290 --> 00:30:31.980
We can't declare victory and
go home because the seeds

00:30:31.980 --> 00:30:34.790
of countless tragedies
are still out there now.

00:30:34.790 --> 00:30:38.120 position:56%
Who's going to provide psychological
counseling for these young Ahmad?

00:30:38.120 --> 00:30:40.160
Who's going to rebuild
his city and his school?

00:30:40.160 --> 00:30:42.750
Who's going to rebuild the
economy and offer hope for a job

00:30:42.750 --> 00:30:44.550
and a family someday in the future?

00:30:44.550 --> 00:30:46.880
It's overwhelming to think
about the size of this task

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:49.510
but it's what is important
not just for moral reasons

00:30:49.510 --> 00:30:50.940
but because of our own security.

00:30:50.940 --> 00:30:53.950
Because if we don't find a
way to address this problem,

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:56.910
you can be assured that we'll
be hearing from Ahmad or boys

00:30:56.910 --> 00:30:58.710
and girls like him in the future.

00:30:58.710 --> 00:31:01.850
You can be confident that the kind
of extremism and the brutality

00:31:01.850 --> 00:31:04.670
that we've witnessed in the
last two years will come back

00:31:04.670 --> 00:31:06.670
to us again and again.

00:31:06.670 --> 00:31:07.970
Thank you for your time.

