00:36:52.740 --> 00:36:54.040
Thank you for the question.

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:55.340
&gt;&gt; Yeah. But again,
looking at your book,

00:36:55.340 --> 00:36:56.640
it's the history of the program.

00:36:56.640 --> 00:36:59.080
So people in ISIS can
show it around to people--

00:36:59.080 --> 00:37:00.380
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:37:00.380 --> 00:37:01.680
&gt;&gt; -- because you've
documented their heroes.

00:37:01.680 --> 00:37:03.770 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah, that is true.

00:37:03.770 --> 00:37:06.460
And the book, because of the
Pulitzer, it's coming out in a lot

00:37:06.460 --> 00:37:07.780
of languages including Arabic.

00:37:07.780 --> 00:37:09.780
So that's something I think about.

00:37:09.780 --> 00:37:11.160
Thank you.

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:13.570
&gt;&gt; I want to ask a
question as a journalist

00:37:13.570 --> 00:37:16.630
who really admires what you do and
really appreciates the craft and--

00:37:16.630 --> 00:37:17.930
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Thank you.

00:37:17.930 --> 00:37:19.650
&gt;&gt; -- believe that your book
ranks with "The Looming Towers",

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:23.290
an outstanding piece of
nonfiction narrative.

00:37:23.290 --> 00:37:25.960
And it's a craft question,
how did you--

00:37:25.960 --> 00:37:28.060
it sounds like you stored it

00:37:28.060 --> 00:37:33.570 position:56%
with some intelligence agents
presumably off the record in Jordan.

00:37:33.570 --> 00:37:34.870
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:37:34.870 --> 00:37:36.170
&gt;&gt; That's my guess.

00:37:36.170 --> 00:37:37.670
