00:40:14.540 --> 00:40:15.840
&gt;&gt; Can you get to explain the
point of terminology, please?

00:40:15.840 --> 00:40:17.140
You speak of ISIS.

00:40:17.140 --> 00:40:18.440
I heard some officials including
the president speak of ISIL.

00:40:18.440 --> 00:40:19.740
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:40:19.740 --> 00:40:21.800
&gt;&gt; And then in addition, I've
heard others used the term dash.

00:40:21.800 --> 00:40:23.100
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:40:23.100 --> 00:40:24.400
&gt;&gt; Could you explain
those three, please?

00:40:24.400 --> 00:40:25.700
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:40:25.700 --> 00:40:27.000
If I could get away with using
dash and people knew what I meant

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:28.650
and I was not just
talking about Morse code

00:40:28.650 --> 00:40:30.430
or something, they--
I would use that.

00:40:30.430 --> 00:40:32.620
And the reason is, it
really all boils down to--

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:36.430
an attempt to transliterate Arabic,
which doesn't always happen easily.

00:40:36.430 --> 00:40:39.360
So what ISIS calls itself is
now just the Islamic State

00:40:39.360 --> 00:40:41.960
but it's the Islamic
State of Iraq and al-Sham.

00:40:41.960 --> 00:40:45.080
It sounds like an S for the
second S in the abbreviation,

00:40:45.080 --> 00:40:47.360
which might be Syria, but
it's not really Syria.

00:40:47.360 --> 00:40:50.620
Sham is this big region,
essentially ignoring history

00:40:50.620 --> 00:40:53.190
of the last century, ignoring
countries that were created

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:57.020
like Syria, Jordan and Israel
that didn't exist 110 years ago,

00:40:57.020 --> 00:41:01.740
and just lumping it together in
this ancient place called Sham.

00:41:01.740 --> 00:41:05.030
And so when you hear ISIS,
people are saying Sham.

00:41:05.030 --> 00:41:07.190
If you're ISIL people
are saying Levant

00:41:07.190 --> 00:41:10.220
which is essentially the English
term that translates to al-Sham.

00:41:10.220 --> 00:41:11.520
And so that's people call it ISIL.

00:41:11.520 --> 00:41:13.440
So I'm not trying to be
clever or cute or trying

00:41:13.440 --> 00:41:14.740
to be politically correct.

00:41:14.740 --> 00:41:17.100
It's really just a struggle
to figure out a proper way

00:41:17.100 --> 00:41:18.870
to transliterate the words.

00:41:18.870 --> 00:41:20.170
But, thank you for that.

00:41:20.170 --> 00:41:21.470
&gt;&gt; Thank you.

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:22.770
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Let's do one more.

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:24.070
&gt;&gt; Hello, sir.

00:41:24.070 --> 00:41:25.370
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Hi.

00:41:25.370 --> 00:41:27.690
&gt;&gt; My question is, what role if
any do you feel that our media

00:41:27.690 --> 00:41:31.730
and in Europe play in creating an
atmosphere that makes it easier

00:41:31.730 --> 00:41:34.920 position:56%
for groups like ISIS to recruit in--

00:41:34.920 --> 00:41:36.220
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:41:36.220 --> 00:41:40.320 position:56%
&gt;&gt; -- places like, you know, Orlando
where, you know, that man was--

00:41:40.320 --> 00:41:41.620
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: Yeah.

00:41:41.620 --> 00:41:43.440
&gt;&gt; -- very familiar with ISIS and
Western Europe and Northern Europe?

00:41:43.440 --> 00:41:44.800
&gt;&gt; Joby Warrick: That's a good
question and it's something

00:41:44.800 --> 00:41:46.630
that we wrestle with
at the Washington Post

00:41:46.630 --> 00:41:48.130
and on up to Marty's level.

00:41:48.130 --> 00:41:51.420
It's-- We do take very
seriously the fact

00:41:51.420 --> 00:41:55.910 position:56%
that our words sometimes can agitate
and excite as well as inform.

00:41:55.910 --> 00:41:57.560
And so we do try to be restrained.

00:41:57.560 --> 00:41:59.630
I mean, there's all kinds of,
like, we're having a discussion

00:41:59.630 --> 00:42:03.130 position:56%
about an article we're trying to put
together now that involves videos.

00:42:03.130 --> 00:42:04.530
How much do you show?

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:06.040
We need to show enough to be able

00:42:06.040 --> 00:42:09.210
to help people understand the
situation, not enough to be kind

00:42:09.210 --> 00:42:13.070 position:56%
of gratuitously, you know,
pruriently, you know, obscene really

00:42:13.070 --> 00:42:14.370
with the level of violence.

00:42:14.370 --> 00:42:17.810
But what I do feel now that we
have an important role to play

00:42:17.810 --> 00:42:21.810
and it's this, ISIS is being--

00:42:21.810 --> 00:42:23.960
They're losing ground
at propaganda war

00:42:23.960 --> 00:42:26.850
because people are understanding
now what they're really about.

00:42:26.850 --> 00:42:29.900
They might see these slick videos
that you get on the internet

00:42:29.900 --> 00:42:31.340 position:56%
but the people coming out of Raqqah,

00:42:31.340 --> 00:42:34.580
the people who are fleeing
those countries had been abused

00:42:34.580 --> 00:42:36.890
and just see these
people as barbarians

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:38.530
who are anything but Islamic.

00:42:38.530 --> 00:42:41.810
The more we can tell those
stories and set people straight

00:42:41.810 --> 00:42:45.620
about what ISIS is really about
destroy their own mythology.

00:42:45.620 --> 00:42:47.930
I think that's a great
contribution to their defeat

00:42:47.930 --> 00:42:49.530
and I don't mind saying that.

00:42:49.530 --> 00:42:50.830
&gt;&gt; All right.

